questlog (1.2.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Sessions list: the view filters leave the toolbar for the list's own strip as lenses - Running and Bookmarked latch independently (both on means the rows that are both), and a Model checklist excludes models rather than choosing one; a count says what an active lens hides from the search's cut; an expand-all button heads the strip.
  * Sessions list: an A/H multiplier column replaces H% (how many times the machine outworked the human), and a Ctx% column shows how full a session's context sits if resumed.
  * Sessions list: startup paints the first rows in under a second on a busy host (was ~10s); the window maps before the corpus scan runs, and each scan chunk paints what it added.
  * Sessions list: a hit on a former name renders as a breadcrumb; a session-names search region matches a session's title history; hovering a clipped snippet reveals its whole stored line; a folder heading selects, carries a menu, and can scope the search to itself.
  * Session viewer: the transcript becomes a streaming document of foldable regions - turns fold, tool noise hides behind a per-turn stub, and fold-all reads the Turns tab as a table of contents; a Quotes tab lists the session's quoted passages and jumps to them; each assistant turn is chipped with its model; tool results read as TOOL RESULT, not USER; a hovering ⧉ copies the message under the pointer; the index band and transcript trade height across a draggable sash.
  * Toolbar: the Restrict box folds to a chip summary that keeps its chips; the find bar says where you are and the index band points at the same hit.
  * CLI: the command line is declared once through ocmdline, so the help and the parser agree; a --markdown output mode joins --json and --shortstat; context flags -A/-B/-C return whole messages around each hit, in json and markdown; the installed claude command teaches the same flags.
  * Modules: the widget and harness layers publish as root-level Tcl modules (streamtree, streamdoc, tkdown, facetbar, leash, steward, tallyman, ocmdline, deadman), installed by every package.
  * GUI: the cost-worker thread resolves tallyman from modules/ and vendor/, matching the entry script's module path, so per-session cost and the A/H multiplier column populate from the first launch.

